Chris:
	I was just about to post this question when I saw your post:
Have any of you SCA fighters used (or seen used) successfully any parrying
weapons?  I would love to know how well they work in "actual" combat, and
how good a model of medieval combat you people believe SCA combat is.  I
went to one fight about 10 years ago, got my legs "cut off" in about 10
seconds, and was completely bewildered. :-)   Anyone care to run down the
pros and cons of shields vs. parrying weapons vs. single weapons?  (Send
your responses directly to me if you think they are too dull for the
list :-)

Tabby:
	*If* you run in a system where illusions can kill people, then
IMHO, the only logical explanation (of magic can be explained logically)
is that the illusion fools the mind enough to have physical effects.
If you accept that idea, you can run that in a couple of different ways:
	A)  The victim believes s/he is being impaled/burned or whatever
nasty thing is happening to them, but shows no damage to neutral observers.
The victim, however, believes so strongly that they create the pain, and
if the illusion is strong enough, they literally "scare themselves to death."
	B)  As above except that the mind/soul has enough power over the
body to actually create the changes it believes to have occured (but only
to the best of its ability).  It might be able to produce wounds, and
could certainly mimic the effects of a disease.  Victim might have a fever,
waste away, etc, but wouldn't *really* have the disease (it couldn't be
caught by another character, for example).
	In either case, I don't think the *illusion* should have the
power to create.  If someone takes damage from an illusionary disease
(how do you convince someone they have an illusionary disease, btw?),
it should not be because the illusion created the disease.  If someone
suffocates because of an illusionary bag over their head (which I would
rule as possible) it should not be because the bag is at all real.  Other-
wise illusion becomes even more powerful as a form of creation magic.

	This is why I hate illusions.  I realize that your question assumes
that illusions can kill, but if you have any power over this, you might
want to reconsider it.  It makes illusions very powerful and opens several
cans of worms.  Can I be healed by drinking an illusionary healing potion?
Can I turn into a deity by drinking an illusionary potion of "polymorph
into deity?"... you get the idea.

							-Jeff
