From: Bill Barney <uunet!pucc.PRINCETON.EDU!IDWXB%ASUACAD.BITNET>
Subject:      sexism and illusions
To: Multiple recipients of list GMAST-L <GMAST-L@UTCVM>
Status: RO

First, I think there are a few very well-known archetypes (that is the
definition of archetype isn't it?) which give rise to the 'sexism' charge.
For instance the covers to "<insert noun phrase here> of Gor."  Which OUGHT
to be sexist because the books are pretty blatantly sexist too.  I think
the Conan books were like that too.  Obviously this sells books on the premise
that the content of the book is somehow related to the cover; same prinicple
they use to sell trashy romances and sleazy westerns.  I don't think that the
same prinicple applies to games--they're much more expensive and much less
likely to contain steamy narratives--but I'm sure it probably has some small
effect.  And yes, there is a lot of fantasy art which isn't sexist.

As Ananda pointed out it is very hard to debate the effects of illusions
because illusion mechanics are so different from game to game.  In my own
game I observe the following basic rules:

 1)Illusions are VISUAL.  (The more complex spells can also be audio, thermal,
   etc.)  If you cannot sense the illusion it has no effect on you.  A visual
   illusion cast behind someone will not affect them unless you can get them
   to turn around.

 2)The ONLY effects of an illusion result from the mind of the victim.  I do
   permit illusions to cause damage, although normal illusions (not P-killer)
   cannot cause death; only unconsciousness and possible psych complications.
   This works great in ADND where "hit points" are an amalgamation of factors
   including stamina, stress, "coolness", etc. and do not just represent
   physical damage.  A phantasmal crossbow bolt would have an effect on the
   morale of the person who was shot, IF he could be convinced that he was hit.
   A phantasmal fireball might have some effect on a person if he had
   experienced fireballs before and was terrified of them.  Of course such an
   illusion would probably fall flat without thermal and auditory components.

   From rule two, it follows that phantasmal armor would affect the way in
   which the blow was struck but not physically affect the blow.  For instance,
   a dagger-wielding orc facing an opponent in illusionary plate might think,
   "hmm, my dagger won't pierce that; I'll attack someone else."  On the other
   hand the same orc with a bastard sword might reason "he's got plate armor,
   I better swing harder."  So it could have the opposite of the desired
   effect.

Regarding damage, it is true that all sensation takes place in the brain and
the nerves are only I/O devices.  Probably most of you have had the experience
of "burning" yourself with cold water that you expected to be hot.  Thus a
character under attack from illusionary crossbow bolts might feel a hit if he
truly expected it to come.  On the other hand, as in the "hot" water example,
he might immediately afterwards realize that he hadn't been hit, as there is
no blood, no bolt shaft sticking out of his armor, etc.  Thus the only effect
of that illusion would be to distract him for a round or maybe a few, while
he tried to sort out what happened.  (On the other hand, a GM might rule that
in the "fog of combat" the victim was not sufficiently clear-minded to realize
all this and lost some hit points in terms of disorientation.)

As a player, it depends on what the GM's philosophy is, but I usually try to
avoid person-affecting illusions for that reason.  I prefer distance illusions
that obscure, confuse, distract, or misdirect.  Another question you might
ask yourselves is "when an illusion is disbelieved (strictly ADND here) does
it vanish, or does the victim simply realize that it is an illusion?"  For
instance, take an illusion of a stone wall obscuring a corridor.  Anyone
successfully disbelieving THAT illusion will be no better off than when they
started (at least in my game).  They will realize that they can walk through
the wall, but they still cannot see through it.  If there are archers on the
other side, they can't see them either (although the archers are at a similar
disadvantage).  If there is a deep pit on the other side, they won't know until
they step through.

About the nastiest thing I ever saw done, and unfortunately it was done to ME,
was a GM who used an illusionary wraith.  My character was familiar with
non-corporeal, level-draining undead, and though he had never seen a wraith
before, he had a pretty good idea of what it was and what its powers were.
I lost many levels to this creature before its creator took a hit which spoiled
the spell.  Even then the shock was great enough that it took a few hours for
me to be functioning fully.  Of course the illusion would have no effect on
any character who had never experienced or heard of level draining undead,
except of course for fear.  Ignorance can be bliss, sometimes.

So what would be the effect of an illusionary chainmail bikini?

Bill Barney
