By the way:

What happens if someone makes an illusionary opening in a wall, affecting all
senses? Is one able to walk through it?
Reminds me of an old trap: a waterfall falling in front an opening in the wall.
There is an illusion of an opening (in fact, the opening) and another
of a water fall cast over it. Our intrepid explorers will soon doubt the
reality of the illusionary waterfall, make their saving throw, and walk
through it. But there IS a waterfall.

Illusions affect the perception, but have no physical reality other than
the physics of perception. On the other hand, I can't see any difference
between real and illusionary pain. What now?

Do people really die in sleep from what they dream? How come we know that?
People are said to have died from a sudden experience of fear, but not everyone
ought to be prone to it.

All of this depends on a set of premises that many won't agree to either for
being too few or too many. Illusions should, IMO, do nothing else than change
the input for CONSCIENT thought, not being able to trigger even a knee-jerk or
other reflex. IMO, everything else is too real to be called an illusion.
   Benedikt
