From: Dave Boddie <uunet!pucc.PRINCETON.EDU!dboddie%UAFHP.UARK.EDU>
Subject:      Re: sexism and illusions
X-To:         Gamemasters Interest Group
              <GMAST-L%UTCVM.BITNET@pucc.PRINCETON.EDU>
To: Multiple recipients of list GMAST-L <GMAST-L@UTCVM>
In-Reply-To:  from "Benedikt Rosenau" at Aug 15, 91 3:31 pm
Status: RO

I think that we are throwing and missing at the target here about illusions.
If you will recall, someone stated that illusions 'changed the perceptions of
the victim'. This is the main function of the illusion power.

Since I would classify sight as a main sense, and that all others are second-
ary, I would say that sight sense takes up a majority of a person's perception
of the world around him. Even if an illusion was sight only, it would still
cause the person to perceive that something was there. Illusions also have a
'dulling' effect on the other senses. To prove my point, I am going to say
this:

In the past I have had a lot of friends who took heavy drugs like acid. From
what I have heard, IMHO, acid severely alters a person's sight perceptions,
allowing him or her to see illusions unleashed by his subconscious mind. And
even though the person knew that the illusions were false, and that he could
reach out and touch them, smell them, etc, he still could not change his
perception of what was happening. If this illusion was a hostile one (my
friend once got attacked by a phone), it puts undue stress on the system
(natural reaction). If this continues, or the perceptions seem deadly, I
would rule that the victim of the illusions *might* (5%-10% chance?) die
from system shock. I am not saying that they should kill all the time, I
am saying that there is a *chance* of killing.

I also think that the effectiveness of an illusion also depends on the
special effect, i.e. the description of the illusion. I think that illusive
armor is stupid, just causes the opponent to swing harder (I know...I have
seen, and been in several SCA fights...nothing special...I just authorized
in sword and shield) to do more damage. However, an illusive weapon *might*
be effective in combat, but unless it had some form of special function, it
should not kill. Only when an illusion is overwhelmingly frightful should it
be considered a killing blow...and then it should have a *chance*. Such ex-
amples would be: falling into a lake/pit/whatever of lava, falling from a
distance that you know you will die from (in AD&D, a high level character can
fall a great distance, which I think is stupid), the grim reaper cutting you
in half with his scythe, etc...you know what I mean. Stuff you *know* you can
instantly die from.

In conclusion, I would like to add that if illusions are powerful enough to
affect the mind as well as they do, then there should be some sort of real
use in it besides that creating goofy pictures of your surroundings. You are
dealing with the human (or other) nervous system here!

Dave Boddie
aka Malaak al Maheem
Shire March of the Grimfells
Calontir

