     First I'ld like to say that in general I like illusions.  They require

more interaction and imagination than most spells.  Yes they can be
incredably powerful, BUT ONLY IF THEY ARE BELIEVED!  That's the big draw
back.  They're not as effective against smart opponents.

     Now a few specific responses:

** Re: Tabby <MUALLEMA%ECUVM1.BITNET@pucc.PRINCETON.EDU>

     I'ld say no to illusionary diseases and heart attacks because of the
lack of understanding of the workings of the human body.  Illusions only work
if both the caster and the victim understand the effects of the illusion.
That's why there are incredible bonuses for the victim if the caster is
trying to make an illusion of something he's never seen.

     But even assuming that it did work, what caster is going to maintain a
spell that requires concentration and line-of-sight for the time it would
take a disease to run it's course?  Imagine a mage following his victim
everywhere.  Pretty soon the victim will either attack the mage out of
frustration or call the local constable to take care of this wacko.

** Re: Rob  <STURNKIN%EKU.bitnet@uunet.uu.net>

     I'ld say illusionary armor works assuming the opponent believes it.
It'ld be like the shield spell that way.  Of course if the mage then casts a
spell the opponent would get a pretty good modifier to disbelieve the
illusion (he know's mages don't wear armor).

     I'ld also give him a new save everytime he would have hit the mage but
didn't because of the illusionary AC.  That simulates the chance that the
mage doesn't understand as well as his opponent the way armor reacts when
struck.

** Re: Bill Barney <IDWXB%ASUACAD.BITNET@pucc.PRINCETON.EDU>

Trust bill to come up with the really pertant question:
"So what would be the effect of an illusionary chainmail bikini?"

     The enemy would probably die laughing!  So illusions can kill! ;-)

-dlw
