>From:         Mysto king of Phrygia ruler of many servant to none!
>              <STURNKIN@EKU.BITNET>

>You say an Illusonary Orc can kill someone. So if a real Orc come up to a mage
>and doens't disbelieve he will see the aurmor. And to him it will be real. So
>to him it will protect. Now what if you put the aurmor on the Orc he thinks it
>is still real so to hime it will protect him as well. Now wouldn't it? It
>might not actually but to him it would am I right??

The idea of illusions having real effects is based on the apparent fact that
the mind can cause physical changes to one's OWN body without apparent physical
input.  In other words, you feel pain in your mind; thus a mind affecting spell
can make you feel pain even if nothing touches you.

Your mind CAN'T affect your external surroundings.  Thus if the orc saw a mage
wearing armor, he might believe it is real, but his belief would not MAKE it
real because the armor is a physical object outside the sphere of influence
of the orc's mind.  By the same token, you might by illusion convince the orc
he can fly, but he will not really be flying and he will not go anywhere; he'll
just stand on the ground and flap his arms.

On the other hand, if you attack that same orc with a sword and the orc
believes it's real, the orc will expect to feel pain when hit.  The brain can
feel pain without outside intervention!  That's within its sphere of influence.
So the illusionary sword will have a real effect; the illusionary armor won't.

Another way of looking at it is that the illusionary sword acts on the orc.
The mage's illusionary armor acts on the orc's sword.  Since the orc's sword
is nonsentient, it cannot be affected by the illusion.  If the orc were to
beat on the mage with his fist, the "armor" might cause pain to the orc--but
it still would not protect the mage a bit!

- Bill

