Subject:      Acid Dreams
To: Multiple recipients of list GMAST-L <GMAST-L@UTCVM>
Status: RO

Hello, what I have to say is perhaps unrelated to Gmast, but I would like to
clear up something that Dave Boddie mentioned in relation to acid.  Most
peoples have startlingly wrong misconceptions about that, and other drugs, and
I felt it was important for me to express the truth.

>From: Dave Boddie <dboddie@UAFHP.UARK.EDU>
>Subj: Re: sexism and illusions
>
>In the past I have had a lot of friends who took heavy drugs like acid. From
>what I have heard, IMHO, acid severely alters a person's sight perceptions,
>allowing him or her to see illusions unleashed by his subconscious mind. And
>even though the person knew that the illusions were false, and that he could
>reach out and touch them, smell them, etc, he still could not change his
>perception of what was happening. If this illusion was a hostile one (my
>friend once got attacked by a phone), it puts undue stress on the system
>(natural reaction). If this continues, or the perceptions seem deadly, I

I'm sorry, Dave, but your friend was having a bit of fun at your expense.
Acid, indeed, *any* psychodelic drug does *not* "allow one to see illusions
unleashed by his subconcious mind".  It does subtly alter ones perceptions but
in no way would make a phone seem as if it were about to attack or pink
elephants jump out of the walls.  That sort of thing is an unfortunate fallacy
that many people share.  The actual effects of psychoactive drugs are very
subtle; i.e. if one does not concentrate one will not realise much is going on
at all.  The colors of the room may seem brighter, the sounds of Beethoven's
9th may seem more immediate, you may even be able to concentrate on the
minutest of detail for periods of time.  Also, acid does not "distract" as the
pink elephant argument suggests, ones perceptions are not "flawed".  A person
under the influence of psychodelic drugs, basically, is *more* aware than you
are I.  (An opposite effect from narcotics such as beer.)

>Dave Boddie


--David

