A quick comment:

     I had said I felt illusionary armor would work.  This is the rationale
(not that magic needs to be rational - it is magic): If the opponent believes
that the sword he's weilding has struck armor it can't penetrate wouldn't he
subconciously stop his swing in order to pull back and swing on a differnt
area where he might be effective?  Affording the "wearer" of such armor at
least some protection?  There are a lot of problems with the realism of
this:  Someone weilding a mace vs illusionary plate would probably not
stop the swing, etc.  But AD&D combat is pretty inexact anyway.

     I'ld be willing to allow it with the provisions mentioned before plus
the comment that the first time the mage actually gets hit the spell is
likely to break from his lack of concentration.

     It doesn't seem a particularly useful application of an illusion anyway.
Any mage who finds himself in melee and uses an illusion spell to create
armor instead of using it to get himself out of combat is in deep sneakers
anyway.

