Dave Wetzel:  You say that you would not allow a disease or heart attack
illusion to work because of the lack of knowledge on the part of the
victim of how diseases etc work.  Would you let an illusion of a magic
missile work on a grunt fighter who doesn't understand how magic works?
(I still don't understand how you could cast the illusion of a heart
attack--at least not if illusions are supposed to be externally observable).
I would think that a disease like Bubonic plague (which many people in the
middle ages were all too familiar with) could cause death (in a campaign
where illusions cause death) because 1) it creates observable effects--
the black "buboes," and 2) the victim would (probably) know it is fatal.

Dave Boddie:  No, I don't think we were "throwing and missing the mark"
about illusions.  Most of us were responding directly to Tabby's question
which assumes that illusions can kill.  The discussion has now shifted, and
I agree with many people that the easiest and best way (in terms of game
balance and consistant interpretation of spell effects) to run illusions
is to rule that they are only observable hoaxes, like holograms, etc.

David Giridot:  I run illusions in a similar way.  "Programming" an illusion
would be very difficult.  If the caster was controlling the illusion, s/he
might be able to program it to respond the way it would be expected to, but
if the illusion is to be cast and then left unattended, it would be hard to
cover all the bases.  In some game systems it may be possible to have another
kind of programmed illusion which is linked with a telepathy magic.  This
sort of spell would be very difficult, but could make the illusion act the
way the victim expected it to (like the Star Trek episode "Shore Leave").

							-Jeff
