From: "Neuromancer (Girardot, David)" <uunet!pucc.PRINCETON.EDU!GIRARDOT%DICKINSN.BITNET>
Subject:      Illusions
To: Multiple recipients of list GMAST-L <GMAST-L@UTCVM>
Status: RO

The following is my own estimation of how illusions should work, and I do not
propose to say that it is *the* way; only to offer a possible viewpoint.
Having said that...

                        ILLUSIONS

Illusions are, simply, a pattern woven by the caster of the illusion, that has
an effect similar to hypnosis on the minds of all but the caster who percieve
the pattern.  These patterns may be woven of a number of different varieties
each with their differing effects.  Whatever the type though, all hold a few
characteristics in common.

First of all, the reality the pattern produces is
_entirely_in_the_mind_of_the_beholder_.  Such a contention is fairly simple to
understand until one considers the added complexity of multiple beholders.
Suppose a pattern is woven onto victim 1 such as that his hair is on fire.
Victim 2 sees this.  There are two possible outcomes.  First: victim runs
around screaming and victim 2 wonders what all the fuss was about.  Second:
victim 1 runs, and victim 2 is alarmed that victim 1's hair is on fire.
However, mindless objects cannot be affected by the pattern.  So what if
victim 2 pours some water on victim 1's head?  The water doesn't know victim
1's head should appear to be on fire.  If the pattern were not sufficiently
complex to recognize the action of water and know to fizzle out it is entirely
concievable that to our victims, the water will appear to have no effect.
Addtionally, unless the pattern is sufficiently complex to dictate that victim
1's hair will begin to show the damage that fire will produce, victim 1 will
not suffer any beyond a general sort of upset.

Thus, we see that an illusion is limited by the complexity of its own pattern.
 A pattern sufficiently complex can have truly amazing effect.  Consider a
sort of pattern woven onto a victim such that he perceives his hair is on
fire, such that if not "put out" by water, etc. it will begin to burn his head
and skin, such that eventually the damage will be so great that the victim
will die.  The effect of such an elaborate illusion would, at best, knock out
the victim if he could not put the fire out (he would appear to be consumed by
flame).

The simplest pattern to create is known as an Image.  An image affects only
the eyes of all who behold it.

A complex pattern is whats known as a Program.  This is an "interactive" image
that comes in two varieties, and is often quite complex to affect all senses
and have a limited interaction with the inanimate similated by fooling the
mind.  This is accomlished in the example already mentioned.  A fire Program
could be made such that it fizzeles when it comes in contact with water.
Programs tend to come in two varieties, depending upon whether their effect is
Internal, or Complex.  Internal affects individuals.  I.E.  a fire Program
Internal would cause victims to percieve fire, but they could dismiss the
Program by the fact that each would not notice the program's effects on the
other.  Needless to say, Internal is the easiest program.  A Complex Program
not only works internally, but externally also, so that a number of victims
experience the Program collaboratively also.  Complex programs are inherently
difficulty, especially with tactile programs experienced by a large number of
individuals.

Patterns remain as long as they are energised by the caster, with one
exception.  Their memory may remain in the victim's mind long after the
pattern has ceased to exist, and this may "self-simulate" the patterns
internal effects indefinitely.  Example, consider a a warrior entirely too
sure of himself.  He becomes victim of an Internal Program such that he is
especially skilled against demonkind.  Because of his own hubris, the danger
is that the warrior may continue to beleive the pattern long after it is gone.

A pattern can only be as complex as it is designed to be.  The difficulty of
creating and maintaining a pattern is proportional to its complexity.
General, anything beyond Images requires months of research and effort to gain
the expertise neccesary to weave a good pattern.  Note that patterns, once
reseacrhed, can then be used easily.  Think of Pattern Programs just like a
computer program, though.  Even at the expert level, it takes hours of
programming to create a pattern that works properly.

One last note, Illusion Patterns are the basis of real magic.  I.E, they are
creation of the unreal, whereas magic can create the real.  Illusions, because
they create so little reality, are (besides the time) quite easy to make.
Magick, because it creates real change in the world (for however long) is more
difficult.  However, there is a third category of creation that is between the
two.  Call it a quasi-real pattern.  It is creation that is not real as far as
the universe is concerned, and yet is.  At any rate, the secret of its
creation is carefully guarded, if it exists at all -- for the technique allows
the de facto creation of magic without any effort.  There is, however, a
price.  It is as if the universe is tricked into accepting the quasi-pattern,
and then realises its mistake (to late to extract energy from the magician).
Well, the universe must balance things somehow, so the fabric of reality is
altered slightly to accept the quasi-pattern.  An example in legend is of the
mage Kenephoreus creating a quasi-real apple that caused the nose of king
Refuild half a world away, to turn blue.

The most successful patterns are those that are subtle rather than complex.
AN example is the Aprentice Yixor's enterprising spell of invisibility that
achieves the effect, not by complex warping of light and photo-displacement
effects, but my causing the mind to "shy away" from whatever is marked by the
pattern.

--David


--David M Girardot

Girardot@dickinsn.bitnet
