ON SUBSERVIENCE

Not only are womnen typically subservient in the
 "mostly-accurate-medieval-society" fantasy, they are also typically
sunservient in the _Conan_ series books, the _Gor_ books,
the _Tarzan_ books, the _Mars_ books, and any host of other "mighty thewed
barbarian" epics- which I think is the originating fantasy for the
chainmail bikini.

Even a lot, maybe most, of contemporary fantasy
involves some male character saving everyone through ther ingenuity and
skill.  But they are sensitive at least!;-)

There are notable exceptions- Mercedes Lackey is often so anti-male(hetero-
sexual male anyways) that it hurts.;-)  She represents the reflection, on
the other side of the "mighty thewed barbarian".  Marion Zimmer Bradley
often has strong female characters, and weak male characters.;-)
Even Robert Howard had his strong female characters- Red Sonya, and
Valeria for examples.

THE FOLLOWING IS MY THEORY:
I think it is mildly inaccurate to say that "the reality of the fantasy
genre *is* subservience in women" but it is MOSTLY true.  Why?  Much
of the classic proto-type fanatsy was written in a time when woman's
rights were just starting to be heard.   It was a time dominated by  male
authors.  Conan and Tarzan were the archetypes for much fantasy- thus their
prejudices and tendencies went with the archetype.   Although there is a
much MUCH stronger representation of women now in fantasy literature it is
still a new trend.  The new books coming out tend to be a lot more
"enlightened".

I, for one, will not mock the mighty thewed barbarian.  Yea, it is sometimes
testosterone-laden, sexist  violence- but it can be fun!;-)

In terms of art(oh yeah- we were talking about art!;-)) I also like Frank
 Frazzetta, but I tend to also be turned off by sniveling, subservient
females.  Though chainmail bikinis can be VERY attractive on some bodies!

ON ILLUSIONS

People do die from shock.  Stress, emotional pressure, and sudden sensory
stimuli can cause people to put physical pressure of their cardiovascular
 system.  It seems feasible to me that if someone were frightened enough
they could die of a heart attack.

I have no evidence that people die of fright except hearsay- but I have no
 evidence that they can't either, and the popular opinion is that they can.

The whole question of illusions killing people depends on what kinf of illusion
 they are.  MAgical illusions seem to come in three types:

1)
They effect your sensory organs and stimulate them so that you see, smell,
hear, feel things that are not really there.

I think this type of illusion would be the most difficult to kill with.
I think a person would only die if they were so terrified of dying that
they had a heart attack at the moment the illusion killed them(or
whatever).  I think it is unlikely.

This is how illusions in my campaign work.

2)
They effect the parts of your mind that interpret sensory data and make you
 believe you are seeing things.  This is mor epowerful as it involves
reaching into the persons mind and manipulating their thoughts.  It also allows
 the illusionist potential to access the subjective manner in which
the victim interprets the illusion.  In that sense the illusionist can make
an illusion inherently SCARY as opposed to cretaing an image that the
illusionist thinks will scare the victim.

This type of illusion would be easier to kill with because you could induce
fright and such strong emotions as to put a lot of stress on the perosn,
possibly leading to a stroke or heart attack!

DEpending on how much the GM thinks the mind controls the body it could
also cause bleeding from imaginary sword wounds, sores from imaginary
diseases, etc.

IN my campaign only very sophisticated enchanters can perform this type of
illusion and it usually requires a thorough understanding of the illusionary
magics and the enchantment magics(charm, hypnosis, cause emotion, etc.).

3)
This one is on the wierd side, and in my opinion does not belong in the
illusion discussion.  It is based on the concept that we make our own
reality.   ANd that if the illusionist convinces us of his reality
using his magics then whatecve rthe illusion is is real for whoever it is
cast on. SO basically if the character did not make a perception/
saving throw/magic resistance roll, or whatever, then they would be
enrolled in the illusionists reality and it WOULD BE REAL for them.

Many AD&D illusions seem to be based on this premise.  I think it is
far too powerful to even call it illusion- because if the character can
actually CHANGE the REALITY of his opponent then no magic is more powerful.
ALSO- this mechanism does explain how illusionary armor or weapons or
illusionary bridges could work.  The caster is just changing HIS reality.

I would recommend that spells of this type be scrapped form anyones campaign,
or at least made unbelievably hard.  (In AD&D terms I would add FIVE levels
to many of the illusion spells that are in this catagory.  The ones that
just effect senses are probably fine just where they are).

To answer questions like the plastic bag over the head choking someone and
dying of a long term illusionary illness, you have to decide what kind of
illusions exist and are possible in your campaign.  My reccommendations are
based on MY preference for a realistic, balanced campaign.  I have run
in really FUN campaigns where Phantasmal Forces(an AD&D spell that allows
you to create the illusion of anything in a fairly large area- it is also
the lowest level spell possible{outside of simple tricks and cantrips})
were thrown around like crazy- it just isn't the kind of campaign I would
run.


Tabby says:
>btw, my favorite interpretation of illusion was that Star Trek episode
>when they were in the wild west..  The illusory bullet killed Chekov,
>and then when Spock dispelled the illusion, he 'came back to life',

Actually Spock didn't dispel the illusion he mad eit possible for McCoy,
Scotty, and Kirk to see that it was an Illusion and not "REALITY"
That struck me as a carefully maintained and constabntlky supervised
illusion because CHekov didn't come back till the Melkotians(I think)
dispelled the illusion themselves.

I think it was a type II illusion!;-)

I JUST got Jeff's post about this!  I agree with it, of course!

