Sharon:  You said you had a ranger who cast an illusion of a good foot
and then walked back to town with it (is that correct?)  If that is the
case, I wouldn't have let you do that, even if other people don't disbelieve
in it.  The fact is that the ranger *knows* that it is not real.  I would
rule that if a person *knows* that something is an illusion, they can ignore
the illusion's effects.  (Actually, I would run illusions completely
differently... :-)

	About a decade ago when I was running a D&D campaign, I thought up
two relatively nasty ideas involving illusions.  I used one on my players,
but never was nasty enough to use the other.  I think they might amuse you.

	The party broke into the house of a mysteriously vanished wizard.
They got to the magic library, which the wizard obviously didn't want people
messing with, so he cast a couple of illusions.  First, he cast the illusion
that the room was completely bricked up solid.  On top of that, he cast a
second illusion that the room was a dusty bedroom.
	Sure enough, the party ransacked the house, then said "this can't
just be a dusty bedroom--it must be an illusion."  Unfortunately, one of the
PCs was inside the room when he successfully disbelieved.  He found himself
encased in brick!  Now, years later, they are still trying to figure out what
is real and what is illusion.  Heh heh.

	The other idea I had hinges on the fact that (at least in 1st Ed
AD&D) there was a rule stating that characters gain no experience for killing
illusionary monsters.  My idea was to run them through a long, grueling
dungeon with a super-unbelievably-nasty monster at the end.  When the party
disbelieves in the much-too-tough monster, the entire (illusionary) dungeon
disappears, along with all their hard earned treasure and experience.
	I would not be writing this now if I had actually tried this one...

							-Jeff
