>From:         Dave_Wetzel@VOS.STRATUS.COM

>    It doesn't seem a particularly useful application of an illusion anyway.
>Any mage who finds himself in melee and uses an illusion spell to create
>armor instead of using it to get himself out of combat is in deep sneakers
>anyway.

An excellent point which I had completely forgotten about!  In most games I
have played in or GMed, maintenance of an illusion requires full concentration
of the mage, so if the mage makes himself an illusionary set of armor, he
can then do nothing but stand there and maintain the illusion.  He can't cast
any more spells.  In AD&D anyway, mages (esp. low levels) often face the
problem of running out of spells and/or hit points and becoming virtually
useless.  Even so, I would imagine that it would make more sense to use your
last spell on something that would protect you and any other incapacitated
PC's (i.e. an illusion that you're "not there") than to blow it on something
as dicey as illusionary armor.  (Guess you could put illusionary armor on
someone ELSE without canceling his ability to act, but then see all my other
objections.)

Dave's other argument about 'subconsciously stopping his swing to hit somewhere
more effective' (a paraphrase)--well, it's a matter of opinion.  If you're
talking about subconsciously stopping a blow mid-swing, I doubt it.  If you
are talking about directing the swing to an area not covered or less covered
by the illusionary armor, I would agree, but I don't think it would be very
useful except in certain very specialized situations.

Bill

