     New Disclaimer:  This is all off-the-cuff and relates to worlds where

illusionary magic exists.

Re: "Geoffrey L. Hodge" <glhodge%UMASSMED.UMMED.EDU@pucc.PRINCETON.EDU>

>Dave Wetzel:  You say that you would not allow a disease or heart attack
>illusion to work because of the lack of knowledge on the part of the
>victim of how diseases etc work.  Would you let an illusion of a magic
>missile work on a grunt fighter who doesn't understand how magic works?

     Depends.  First let me say the grunt doesn't need to be able to do
magic, he just needs to understand that when the mage points those little
globs of light at someone they take damage.  Conversely, if the fighter
truely has never seen a magic missile, he wouldn't take damage.

     Here's why, the theory is that the illusion itself doesn't cause effect,
it's the believer's mind that does.  If the believer has no idea what the
effect of this object flying at him will be, he will take no effect from it.
He may cringe from it, not knowing if he's about to become a frog or perhaps
go insane, or get real weak, etc.  But when it hits, if he doesn't know what
will happen nothing will.

     For this reason, we've always played that certain spells can make good
illusions, but most can't.  Fireball is a good example of one that makes a
good illusion because it has a real, understandable, visual effect (being
encased in fire).  I can't image illusionary charm person (unless cast
against a mage who was watching the opponent cast and trying to figure out
what was cast and *believes* it was charm person and then fails his
"disbelieve" save despite his high int and then fails his normal save vs
charm person -- pretty bloody unlikely).

     I don't understand how the effect of a heart attack could be made
with an illusion either (except by making a good scary illusion appear:-).

     As for disease, if both the caster and the victim were healers or
otherwize had a real detailed knowledge of disesase, I suppose it could be
fatal.  But, again, what caster is going to follow his victim around for the
days/weeks/months/years it takes to die from the disease.  Even the plague
took days to actually die from.  The only way I could see this working is if
the two were in a town currently infected with a real nasty plague.  The
caster could cast the illusion of disease on his victim in hopes that the
townsfolk would believe it and toss the "infected" person on the fire with
the rest of the infected people.

     That's the real use of illusions, to make others react to something
that's not real.  Getting them to either achieve an effect for you or to
distract them from you and your friends.

     As an aside, I agree with you Jeff, the ranger with one foot would not
be able to walk on an illusionary one because he *KNOWS* it's not real.  You
can't take the benefit of an illusion you don't believe in just because you
want to believe.  And as GM, I'ld make sure you checked for belief the first
time you tried to use it (and I'ld make it an automatic failure, unless there
was a real good excuse to give the character a chance to believe).  Of course
if they had magically altered the ranger's memory (hypotism, et al),
convincing him that he never lost the foot, he'ld have a normal save to
believe the illusion.  I'm not sure I'ld let him walk on it afterwards
anyway.  I'ld have to think about that.


Dave_Wetzel@vos.stratus.com
