ok.. I know you're sick of this topic, but I want to answer some of the
questions directed at me.  Mainly, to be more specific about how I *do*
run illusions.

The illusion is entirely in the believer's mind.  If an illusory ton of
bricks fell on a believer, he would believe he was dead and act accordingly.
Witnesses who believed the ton of bricks would believe he was dead and act
accordingly.  So if everyone around thought he was dead, he would lie there,
not moving, metabolism slowed almost to death, until he starved, died of
thirst, or someone dispelled the illusion that he had died.
(Once again, I am reminded of the Star Trek where Chekov died from an illusory
bullet, but Spock dispelled the illusion, bringing him back to life.)

So, ok, if a mage wore illusory armor, a blow would still hit him for full
damage, but the victim might think it bounced off the armor, and would swing
even harder the next time.  If he gave someone else the armor, that person
would get hit and think that he hadn't, and might stand there thinking he
was invulnerable until he really died.  If a ranger believed he had an illusory
foot, he would think he was walking along, when really he would be hobbling
along pathetically, doing horrible damage to his stump.  If he had an entire
illusory leg, he would think he was walking along, when really he'd be doing
the curly shuffle.  A mage could create an illusion that he is wielding a
sword, and if he struck a killing blow to a believer, the believer would
believe he was dead:  same as the ton of bricks above.  Ok, so if plague
was common in the world, and someone did Maintain an illusion of plague on
a believer for long enough, i would rule that the believer would think he
was dead.


Ok, Now I have another question:  Have there been any actual instances of
someone under hypnosis being made to believe they had died??   If so,
what happens??  This might shed some light on the subject....


 Tabby
