So, Tabby, did you get the "more intelligent" discussion you wanted?  :-)

One thing no one's mentioned directly, but several people have perhaps alluded
to is psychosomatic effects.  Basically, a psychosomatic illness is a *real*
illness caused by a person's mind.

How might this transfer over into the illusion discussion?  Well, if a person
thinks he's sick because he appears to have a disease, he may well make himself
truly physically sick.  If he sees an arrow sticking out of his chest, with
blood flowing from the wound, his mind may well create the pain such a wound
would cause -- but if he's never had such a wound, the amount of pain his mind
would create could be much greater or lower than it "should" be.  (Okay,
explanation via game mechanic:  an arrow does 1d6 damage.  If the victim here
has never been hit by an arrow before, his mind could cause 1d4 or 1d8 of "pain
damage" as easily as 1d6.)  The aforementioned fighter who's never seen a magic
missle could possibly die if he perceives the missle as lethal magic, or not
even bat an eyelash if he perceives it as nothing more than a little light-
bolt.

As far as people having heart attacks due to fright, I read something about
that in an issue of _Discover_ magazine several years ago.  I believe it said
that such things are not only possible, but at least implied if not stated that
fright-induced heart attacks have happened.

(Brandon:  I like your ideas for adnd mechanics for 'damaging illusions'.  They
just might get used tonight....umm, make that in about ten minutes; I'm late
already....)

--Ananda

