        I suffer from being a few timezones away from you all, so I get huge
bundles of mail when I log in - it also means that other people get to say
all the wonderful things i wanted to say. (Sob, sob)

        Illusionary Armour - well, if you believe that it is real and can
protect you, your mind may well make some changes to the damage you suffer
to reflect that -- and it must work both ways - if an illusion can convince
your mind that you are hurt, then it can also convince your mind that you
aren't, and you won't be.

        However, you obviously can't cast Illusionary armour on yourself,
becuase you would know that it was an illusion, wouldn't you? So a mage has
to cast it on a fighter and not tell the fighter that it is an illusion.

        This pretty much wipes out that ranger with his illusory foot,
doesn't it? and even if someone else cast it for him, and said it was a
"healing" spell, there is no way anyone could maintain a permanent illusion
of that complexity beyond concentration time.

        Actually, given the complexity required for a killing illusion -
it would have to fool several senses simulataneously, it would almost always
have to move convincingly and be "done" with a lot of artistry and skill, they
would be very rare. Since very few of us can, with time, draw a brick that
looks real, then people who can whip up a ton of falling bricks on demand
would be rare. The most regular, and useful, use of illusions in campaigns
I've played in has been to subtly alter the lightening or sound in a limited
area. The worst we ever ran into was last session, in the "halls of the High
 King" where the three watevertheycallem in 2nd Ed hit us with three
different killers simultaneously - the old crushing walls was one - and
all we lost was a few swords, whanged off walls that had illusions cast on
them.

        Mike Cosgrave
